---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

// The two design-aping skills that live in the repo, with provenance taken
// verbatim from their SKILL.md files. `/minimal` is referenced by both as a
// quieter sibling but lives elsewhere.
const styles = [
  {
    n: '01',
    name: 'muller',
    of: 'Josef Müller-Brockmann',
    note: 'A visible, mathematical modular grid carrying large, precisely-set type. Structure comes from column alignment and thin rules — not boxes. One rationed signal-red accent. The grid as an ethic.',
    accent: true,
  },
  {
    n: '02',
    name: 'jetset',
    of: 'Experimental Jetset (Amsterdam)',
    note: 'Pure black Helvetica on pure white. Type IS the image — words filling the surface, set tight and huge. Exactly one flat spot color per piece, used as a field. Flat, hard, zero effects.',
    accent: false,
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Aping the modernists — Andrew Shiau"
  description="Agent skills that generate documents in the voice of the Swiss typographers."
>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="back"><a href="/">← Index</a></div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">01</span></div>
    <div class="c3-12"><h1>Aping the modernists</h1></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <p class="dek c1-8" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
      A set of agent skills that generate self-contained HTML documents in the
      voice of specific design lineages — the Swiss grid, the Amsterdam poster
      studio. You invoke one; the agent renders your content through that
      studio's rules instead of the default machine-made look.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="idea">
      <p class="k">The trick</p>
      <p>The style is encoded as constraints, so the machine can't drift out of it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- meta callout: this site IS an output -->
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="block c1-6">
      <span class="sl">You are looking at one</span>
      <span class="st">This entire site is rendered in the /muller style.</span>
      <span class="sd">Press g to reveal the grid it's built on.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="rule"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">§</span></div>
    <div class="c3-12"><h2>The houses</h2></div>
  </div>

  <!-- The styles as rule-topped columns, not cards -->
  <div class="grid" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
    {styles.map((s) => (
      <div class={s.accent ? 'step accent' : 'step'} style="grid-column:span 6">
        <span class="snum">{s.n}</span>
        <span class="sl">after {s.of}</span>
        <span class="st">/{s.name}</span>
        <span class="sd">{s.note}</span>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="rule"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="facts">
      <div class="frow">
        <div class="fm">Form</div>
        <div class="ftx">
          Each style is a single <b>SKILL.md</b> — a spec of design tokens, a
          grid, and an "anti-slop checklist" the agent must obey. No build step;
          every output is one self-contained HTML file with system Helvetica.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="frow">
        <div class="fm">Why constraints</div>
        <div class="ftx">
          The rules are written as hard <b>MUST / MUST NOT</b> (RFC&nbsp;2119)
          lines, so the model can't quietly drift a piece back toward generic
          "AI look." The reference is the actual work — the book, the posters —
          re-derived, not a vague memory.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="frow">
        <div class="fm">Source</div>
        <div class="ftx">
          Lives in a private repository. <b>Sample output shown here</b> — this
          page is one; source available on request.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
